'La Baie' (pronunciation: /la bÉ/) is one of three boroughs in the city of
Saguenay, Quebec, Canada. It was created during Quebecâs municipal
reorganization in 2002. From 1976 to 2001, it was known as the Town of La Baie,
a municipality composed of the Grande-Baie, Bagotville, and Port-Alfred sectors.

It is located on the bank of the Ha! Ha! Bay (French: baie des Ha! Ha!) at the
mouths of the Ha! Ha! River (French: riviÃ¨re Ha! Ha!) and the Mars River
(French: riviÃ¨re Ã  Mars). La Baie was the first colony built in the Saguenay-Lac-St-
Jean region. It was founded by the SociÃ©tÃ© des Vingt et un who settled the area
in 1838. The depth of the banks of the Ha! Ha! Bayâs waterways facilitated the
rapid development of the regionâs largest harbour facilities after the railways
were built in 1910.

The boroughâs main sources of socio-economic development have been the logging
and the pulp and paper industries since the nineteenth and twentieth centuries
respectively. Aluminum production began in the early 1980s. After the Abitibi-
Consolidated paper mill, one of the main employers of the borough, shut down in
2004, Saguenayâs elected officials decided to invest in La Baieâs tourism
industry by building and operating a port of call for cruise ships in 2008.

Bagotville Airport, the main civilian airport in Saguenay-Lac-St-Jean, is also
located in La Baie. The Canadian Forces Base Bagotville, which shares the same
airfield, is one of only two Canadian military bases that use the Royal
Canadian Air Forceâs CF-18 fighters. The military base is currently the
boroughâs largest employer.

While Chicoutimi and JonquiÃ¨re, the two boroughs that constitute the main urban
core of Saguenay, are located close to each other, La Baie is at a moderate
distance from the city centre. This has created some unique issues for the
borough â for example, while a full-power television or radio station in
Saguenay can serve the entire city from a single transmitter without difficulty,
La Baie is distant enough from the city's urban core that some low-power
broadcasters, such as CKAJ-FM, have had to add separate transmitters to
rebroadcast their signals in La Baie.
